heir ideal borrower someone who was white, propertied, and male. In subsequent decades, the emancipatory promise of debtors’ rights would be tested as women, wage earners, and African Americans seized on their language to challenge other structural inequalities: the dependency of marriage, the exploitation of industrial capitalism, and the oppression of Jim Crow. By reconstructing these forgotten developments—and recovering the experiences of indebted farmwives, sharecroppers, and wage workers—The Price of Misfortune narrates a new history of inequality, coercion, and law amid the early financialization of American capitalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  alegal history, finance capitalism, debtors' rights, inequality, coercion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079732940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226734033423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226734033/original  a978-3-11-079732-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles